	* likely future mitigation commitments of the State and the economic imperative for early and cost-effective action, and
	* the requirement to be able to act quickly in response to economic and environmental occurrences and circumstances;
	* the need to promote sustainable development;
	* the need to take advantage of environmentally sustainable economic opportunities both within and outside the State;
	* the need to achieve the objectives of a national mitigation plan at the least cost to the national economy and adopt measures that are cost-effective and do not impose an unreasonable burden on the Exchequer;
	* relevant scientific or technical advice;
	* the findings of any research on the effectiveness of mitigation measures and adaptation measures;
	* the sectoral mitigation measures included in the national mitigation plan pursuant to
	* that are to be adopted by each Minister of the Government in relation to the matters for which each such Minister of the Government has responsibility;
	* where a national mitigation plan has been approved by the Government, the most recent approved national mitigation plan;
	* any recommendations or advice of the Advisory Council;
	* mitigation measures, specified in a notification to the Minister or the Government under subsection ; and
	* the protection of public health.
	* publish, in such manner as he or she considers appropriate, a draft of the national mitigation plan that he or she proposes to make,
	* publish a notice on the internet and in more than one newspaper circulating in the State inviting members of the public and any interested parties to make submissions in writing in relation to the proposed national mitigation plan within such period (not exceeding 2 months from the date of the publication of the notice) as may be specified in the notice, and

